comments.text:
The Haw Flakes are made from Chinese Hawthorn. The mass-produced candies 
could have also been made with flavouring, so don't quote me on anything. I 
remember it to be very popular among kids maybe a decade ago. They can 
still be found now, and I still like them. But it's recognised as more of a 
"childhood candy".

I don't think I've eaten those squid chips before. Then again, I don't go 
around testing all the chips we have.

I also have no idea what red melon seeds are.

Chicken satay is very popular. If I'm not wrong, lamb satay is also very 
popular, but I prefer chicken as it's usually more tender. You could 
probably find pork and beef as well, if you find hard enough. But usually 
they'll avoid selling those two as pork and beef go against the religion of 
Malays and Indians respectively. It's then grilled and served in that epic 
sauce. That sauce is amazing. Usually, satay is also served with pressed 
rice cakes (just google "satay pressed rice cake"), cucumber, and onion 
pieces on the side.

It would have probably been hard to find tasty Singaporean food without 
them coming to Singapore personally, since most of the popularly recognised 
"Singaporean food" are rice, noodle, or soup dishes.

People who go "This isn't Singapore food! This is *_* food!" need to 
realise that Singapore is formed by immigrants of many different places. 
There are people from cultures all over the world, especially neighbouring 
countries. Malaysian food, Indonesian food, Chinese food, etc. Technically, 
you could consider all Singaporean food to be food of other countries. Grow 
up and stop arguing.﻿
